@node "installation_e" "Installation"
@prev "licence_e"
@next "usage_e"

@{b}Installation@{ub}
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

@{b}System Requirements:@{ub}
- Amiga OS 2.04, or higher.
- At least 1Mb memory.
- Commodore Installer.
- be sure the mathtrans- and the locale-library are  located in your LIBS:
  drawer (both libraries are included with Workbench).

@{b}Installation:@{ub}
It is recommended  that  you  use  the included  installer  script. Simply
double click the install icon and then follow the instructions.
If you do  not  like to  use install  scripts, then  move the  de-crunched
directory onto your hard drive, or other Volume (Zip etc), and ensure that
all files are kept together.
The authors are  not liable  for any  unforeseen  complications  that  may
arise, as this function has had  extensive personal testing! It  works for
us, and we  see no legitimate reason why it  should cause any problems for
any other user.

@endnode



@node "usage_e" "Usage"
@prev "installation_e"
@next "mainscreen_e"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

To facilitate easy use, VideoArchiv is created so every option is accessed
from a button (or keyboard) instead of "pull-down" menus.

Full  control is  attained by  moving your  mouse  pointer over  whichever
option is required, and then clicking. Could not be simpler!
If you prefer to use your  keyboard, then each option can also be accessed
by using each underlined letter, as shown.
Use the Return key when a broken arrow is visible.

@{b}Button Types:@{ub}

@{b}Text Button:@{ub}
  Each action using a text button is executed immediately.

@{b}Cycle Button:@{ub}
  Cycle buttons  are used when  several options are available. Each option
  is accessible, once the required title is shown.
  Cycle buttons can also be controlled by using the Amiga buttons, F6-F10.

@{b}Checkbox:@{ub}
  Checkboxes allow simple on/off commands.
  By default, some boxes will appear either blank or ticked.
  When used  in  conjunction  with  the cycle  buttons, every  VideoArchiv
  option can be altered, and/or customised.

@{b}String Gadget:@{ub}
  String  gadgets (or  string  fields) allow  the user  to enter  data. To
  enable a string gadget, click once: a cursor will then appear.
  If there is  more  than one string  gadget sited on the screen, pressing
  enter will always leave the current string gadget and enable the next.
  Once selected, you can  use the following keyboard  commands for special
  features:
  RAmiga+X           : delete the content of the string gadget.
  Shift+Del          : delete all chars to the left of the cursor.
  Shift+Backspace    : delete all chars to the right of the cursor.
  Shift+Cursor Left  : move the cursor to the first char.
  Shift+Cursor Right : move the cursor to the last char.
  String gadgets can also be controlled by using the Amiga buttons F1-F5.

@{b}List View:@{ub}
  Simply, this  allows  the  user to show, and/or customise, or  view, any
  VideoArchiv list.
  Each list is controlled by  clicking any one of the 6 arrow buttons that
  are sited to the right, while using your mouse.
  The contents of each window list can be highlighted by the mouse cursor;
  but to view the full contents, the 6 arrow buttons (or keyboard options)
  must be used to scroll through each individual list.
  Simple  experimentation will  illustrate the use of these 6 buttons, far
  easier than pages of text! 
  Below are the equivalent keyboard options for the 6 buttons.
  
  Button:      Function:                           Keyboard:
  ------------------------------------------------------------------------
  1.Button     Move up to the top of this list.    Right-Alt+Cursor-Up
  2.Button     Move up to the next "page".         Right-Shift+Cursor-Up
  3.Button     Move up one entry.                  Cursor-Up
  4.Button     Move down one entry.                Cursor-Down
  5.Button     Move down to the next "page".       Right-Shift+Cursor-Down
  6.Button     Move down to the last entry.        Right-Alt+Cursor-Down

  F-Button control: F1-F10
  When view listers are used, the  complete range of F-buttons can be used
  to move through the list.
  ie: F1    - moves to the first entry of the list.
      F10   - moves to the last entry.
      F5    - moves to the middle entry.
      F2-F4 - VA cleverly splits the listed numbers between  the first and
              the middle, and  then  allocates F2, F3, F4 so the  user can
              then move easily by using these F-keys.
      F6-F9 - these F-keys operate in  the same way,  but from  the middle
              to the penultimate entry.
  The larger the database, the more this option will be seen  as very use-
  ful.

@endnode



@node "Intro_e" "Intro (English)"
@next "mainscreen_e"
@prev "usage_e"

@{b}INTRO@{ub}
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

Once the  programme  has  started, the first  screen displayed is  for the
Intro. This shows the author's details.

If not registered, a window will be shown to allow the relevant details to
be added. These  will contain your name, and individual code received from
the authors. Click "Register". This enables all disabled functions.

If you do not have a  password, this window will  allow the "Later" option
to be used until actually registered.

Be aware that the following options are not available if unregistered:
- printing: complete, or part, lists.
- saving any preferences.
These options will only be available when registered.

See @{"Licence" link licence_e 0} on how to register.

@endnode



@node "mainscreen_e" "Main Screen (English)"
@prev "usage_e"
@next "Funktion_ListView_e"

@{b}MainScreen@{ub}
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

Use the "Proceed" button to move from the @{"Intro" link "Intro_e" 0} screen.

The VideoArchiv main screen will appear and the  default message, as shown
in the "File I/O Error," will appear.
Once a file  path is  entered into  the "Load File at Startup" preference,
that file will  be loaded  (by default). This  file name will be  shown in
the centre  top box, between  the VideoArchiv v3.0 and  the "Quit" button.
A progress bar and % number  will show while this  operation is completed.
Sited at the right of the main screen are the six arrow buttons that allow
the user complete freedom to move around any file list.
The 10 main options are represented by the buttons under the main screen.

These options are listed below:

 @{" ListView " link "Funktion_ListView_e" 0}    - Control of the Listview

 @{"   ADD    " link "Funktion_Add_e" 0}    - Add a video to the list.
 @{"   EDIT   " link "Funktion_Edit_e" 0}    - Edit the selected video.
 @{"  DELETE  " link "Funktion_Delete_e" 0}    - Delete the selected video.
 @{" ISSUING  " link "Funktion_Borrow_e" 0}    - Lend a video, and track it.
 @{"   SAVE   " link "Funktion_Save_e" 0}    - Save the video list.
 @{"   LOAD   " link "Funktion_Load_e" 0}    - Load a video list.
 @{"   SORT   " link "Funktion_Sort_e" 0}    - Sort the selected list.
 @{"  SEARCH  " link "Funktion_Search_e" 0}    - Search, matching given parameters.
 @{"  PRINT   " link "Funktion_Print_e" 0}    - Print the complete list, or part.
 @{"  SETUP   " link "Setup_e" 0}    - Edit most preferences (genre, name-lists, etc...)

 @{"   QUIT   " link "Funktion_Quit_e" 0}    - to quit the programme.



 Back to @{"  Main  " link main 0}

@endnode



@node "Funktion_ListView_e" "ListView (English)"
@prev "mainscreen_e"
@next "Funktion_Add_e"

@{b}ListView@{ub}
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

The main screen shows the VideoArchiv database (once created) in a lister.
If the "Edit Film by double click" option  is ticked (sited on the Options
screen) you are able  to highlight any entry on  the main screen, and then
by double clicking, can edit the complete entry.
If a double click is used on an entry without this option ticked, the info
window will appear showing the following information:

                                Main Title

                         Nr     : <Nr>
                         O-Title: <Original Title>
                         Year   : <Year>

                         Length :     Language:
                         Medium :     Age     :
                         Technical: <video speed>, <format>, <medium>

                         Genre   : <genre>
                         Director: <director>
                         Actor(s): <actor(s)>

and also the main header line from the "description" screen.


When you lend  a film, a "+" is displayed  to the right of the film entry.
A double click will show the name and the date of issuing.


 For controlling details see @{"Usage" link "usage_e" 0}.

@endnode



@node "Funktion_Add_e" "Add"
@prev "Funktion_ListView_e"
@next "Funktion_Edit_e"

@{b}Add@{ub} (keyboard: "a")
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

The "Add" button is used to create a new film entry.

Once accessed, the Add screen allows the user to create a video entry with
multiple choice entries, that should satisfy even the most demanding user.

Each of the 8 black boxes are available for data input.
The 2 top left cycle buttons  can be altered manually by moving  the mouse
over each button, to the right, and then clicking until satisfied.
The 4 lower left cycle buttons  can  also be altered  in the same fashion,
or by using the keyboard and the relevant underlined letter.
Each  of  these @{b}6 cycle buttons@{ub} can  then be altered  to  suit  the user's
preferences by entering  the Setup/Options screen. These can then be saved
as the default setting (sorry, registered users only).

Individual data can be entered into each of the following black boxes:
@{b}Nr.   @{ub}: - allows the user to  enter any combination (maximum 4) of letters
          or numbers for identification.
@{b}Length@{ub}: - allows the user to enter up to 4 digits.
@{b}Title @{ub}: - allows the user to enter a title (maximum 45).
@{b}O-Tit @{ub}: - allows the user to  enter an  alternative title, or  to copy the
          original title, by moving the mouse over the arrow button, sited
          at the left of this input box, and clicking.
@{b}Year  @{ub}: - allows the user to enter up to 4 digits.

@{b}Genre @{ub}: - allows the user to enter up to 42 letters to illustrate the type
          of films covered by this numbered entry.
@{b}Direc @{ub}: - allows the  user to enter  up to 42  letters to  illustrate  the
          names of the relevant film directors.
@{b}Actor @{ub}: - allows the  user to enter  up to 42  letters to  illustrate  the
          names of the relevant actors.

Each of the above 3 options  can  have data  added  by using each relevant
arrow button sited to the right of each box. When  each arrow is used, the
relevant "List" will be shown (Genre, Director, Actor), so that any of the
pre-listed names can be  added to each box. Repeated  use of these buttons
will continue to add names, until  the maximum  default number  is reached
(42 letters/spaces).

Below these black boxes is sited the @{b}Description@{ub} button.
When used, (either  by mouse, or  keyboard "d"), the  screen that is shown
allows 12 lines  to be added, in order to better  describe the main entry.
When in use, this screen shows the title of the entry (middle top box) and
its relevant number (middle bottom box).
Use the "OK" button to  return to the  main screen, or "Exit" to return to
the "Add" screen.

Once all data has  been entered  onto the edit and other relevant screens,
use either the "OK" or the "Exit" button (current changes will  be lost).
If no film title has been added  and then the OK option is  used, an error
requester will  be shown:
  "Error - You must enter a film-title."
If this occurs the user can escape by using the "Exit" option.


 Back to @{"MainScreen" link "mainscreen_e" 0}

@endnode



@node "Funktion_Edit_e" "Edit"
@prev "Funktion_Add_e"
@next "Funktion_Delete_e"

@{b}Edit@{ub} (keyboard: "e")
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

Highlight the entry that requires editing by using the mouse.

The Edit screen is accessed by moving the mouse over  the Edit button, and
clicking, or by using  the keyboard "e." If the "double-click edit" option
has been selected from the option screen, there is  no need to use  either
of the above - simply doubleclick the film you want to edit in the lister.

The screen that  appears  is the  same  as described  in @{"Add" link "Funktion_Add_e" 0}, but now all
boxes are filled with the relevant film data.

It is suggested that once the Edit screen has been used and the MainScreen
re-entered, the "Save" button should  be  used to  ensure that  no altera-
tions are lost!


 Back to @{"MainScreen" link "mainscreen_e" 0}

@endnode



@node "Funktion_Delete_e" "Delete"
@prev "Funktion_Edit_e"
@next "Funktion_Borrow_e"

@{b}Delete@{ub} (keyboard: "d")
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

The Delete button allows the user to delete any highlighted entry from the
shown database.

A requester will be shown:
  "Are you sure that you want to delete the selected film?"
The title of the entry will be shown underneath this message.
A choice between 3 options is required:
  Delete   : delete the highlighted film.
  All Erase: delete the complete film list; this must be confirmed.
  Exit     : leave data untouched.

Use with extreme caution. Once deleted the data is LOST!


 Back to @{"MainScreen" link "mainscreen_e" 0}

@endnode



@node "Funktion_Borrow_e" "Issuing"
@prev "Funktion_Delete_e"
@next "Funktion_Load_e"

@{b}Issuing@{ub} (keyboard: "i")
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

This option enables the user to keep a record of any number of videos that
are loaned to others.

Move the  mouse  over the  Issuing button  and click. A small  screen will
appear. The user can  then  enter  any  details  into the  main black  box
(maximum 40 letters or numbers).

The 3 smaller black boxes are  meant to show numbers only (the date!). The
arrow button, sited  to the left, will  input the present date  (dd;mm;yy)
if used (assuming your system contains an "in use" clock).
If no clock, the numbers can be entered manually.

Use the Erase button to delete all entries.

To  exit  this  option  move  the  mouse  over  either the "OK" or  "Exit"
button, then click, to return to the main screen.

This option is only available from the main screen.


 Back to @{"MainScreen" link "mainscreen_e" 0}

@endnode



@node "Funktion_Load_e" "Load"
@prev "Funktion_Borrow_e"
@next "Funktion_Save_e"

@{b}Load@{ub} (keyboard: "l")
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

If no "default file" path  is entered in  the preference file, or the user
wishes to load another file, then this option button is used.

There is a request option to remind the user  if any alterations have been
made to an earlier file, before loading:
  "Request Are you sure you want to load a new file? (current changes will
   be lost!)"
The "Exit" button returns the user to the main screen.
The "OK" button shows a  basic  file  selector, allowing  the user to then
load whichever file is required. 

A user default file  can be indicated  by adding the relevant details into
the 2 black boxes on the "Options" screen (registered users  can save this
setting). See @{"Setup" link Setup_e 0}.


 Back to @{"MainScreen" link "mainscreen_e" 0}

@endnode



@node "Funktion_Save_e" "Save"
@prev "Funktion_Load_e"
@next "Funktion_Sort_e"

@{b}Save@{ub} (keyboard: "s")
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

The save button allows the  user to save any file, via a  standard request
option.


 Back to @{"MainScreen" link "mainscreen_e" 0}

@endnode



@node "Funktion_Sort_e" "Sort"
@prev "Funktion_Save_e"
@next "Funktion_Search_e"

@{b}Sort@{ub} (keyboard: "o")
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

The Sort button allows the  user to sort the contents of the database file
shown on the main screen. This  button  allows the  user almost  unlimited
sort options.

When the  sort option  is chosen  from the  main screen, a Sort  screen is
shown, allowing complete access to the multiple sort options.
This allows the user two options:
Sort Mode: - this allows the user to sort either up, or down.
Sort By  : - this allows the user to sort by using the various parameters,
             in conjunction with the Sort Mode.
             These are: Number; Title; Length; LP/SP; Status.

The "OK" button starts this option. "Exit" closes the  sort option without
sorting.

While sorting, a notice will be shown in the status line:
  "Sorting Please Wait"
A progress bar will be shown moving to the right.

The database  file will  need to be  saved if  a permanent  alteration  is
needed.


 Back to @{"MainScreen" link "mainscreen_e" 0}

@endnode


@node "Funktion_Search_e" "Search"
@prev "Funktion_Sort_e"
@next "Funktion_Print_e"

@{b}Search@{ub} (keyboard: "r")
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

This is the "Piece De Resistance" of the VideoArchiv programme.

The search option screen  allows the user  to customise the search parame-
ters  into  any multiple  combination required. From  large, wide  ranging
results, down  to the  minutest detail, VideoArchiv has  any other  search
option beaten.

The search screen is  composed of 11 "main" search  options, accessed  via
the  cycle  button  in  the  left  corner,  and 10 "other" search  options
accessed by adding a tick to any of the 10 square buttons sited  below the
main search option. The check-box/cycle buttons sited in  the right corner
are to  enable the @{b}Advanced options@{ub}. Each  can  be scrolled  to the  users
preference, and  as long as  the "Enable" option is ticked, they  will  be
used in the search.

The "main" search parameter is set from the cycle  button  and  allows the
following search options:
Title; Original Title; Genre;  Director; Actor; Description; Person,  (can
be used if a title is "on loan"); Date; Length of Film; Year; Number.
Once an option  is chosen, a "search reference" must  be entered  into the
box sited to the right. If  none  is given  and a  search is  initiated an
error  message  will  appear (if  no  advanced  search  options  are  also
selected):
  "Error Search: No search-parameter(s) defined."
Click "OK" and restart the search option, or "Exit" to the main screen.

Options available are:
 - @{b}After present Pos@{ub}: will start  searching from  the  current highlighted
                      entry; not from the first entry.
 - @{b}Match Identical  @{ub}: will only show  videos with relevant data that match
                      exactly the string entered in the string gadget.
 - @{b}Case Sensitive   @{ub}: self-explanatory.
Any can be added to  the search parameters  by adding a tick  to whichever
option (or any  combination) is  required by  moving  the mouse over  each
adjacent button and clicking.


There are now two different search modes:

@{b}Search:@{ub}
Any search results will be shown on a "Search Results" screen. This screen
has  the 6 scroll arrow buttons sited to the  right of the screen, and has
further options shown below the  viewing screen. These  allow  the user to
opt for any of the following:
  - Next   : show the next 50 entries found (or those actually found).
  - Search : do a new search, (will return to the search window).
  - Edit   : edit the highlighted film in the search list.
  - Print  : print the search results.
  - Exit   : return to the main screen.

@{b}Search by step:@{ub}
The "Search by step" is similar but allows single searching. Each entry is
presented in a similar screen to the "info" option; (see @{"ListView" link Funktion_ListView_e 0}).
Once read  click the "Continue" button to move  on and  highlight the next
reference.
The user is able to access the Edit screen for each search entry by moving
the mouse over the "Edit" button, and clicking.


The "Search" option lists  every "found" entry  in a  single lister, while
the  "Search by step" shows  more individual  information and  enables the
user to read the results entry by entry. 

Once satisfied return to the main screen, using "Exit."



Three @{b}search examples@{ub} using the VA default file "Filmlist_Demo.vad":
(be sure the default values are used!).

1) Enter "alien" into the search box then start the search option!
   The default search  setting is shown as "Title," so VA searches for any
   relevant film  with "alien" in the title. In this  example  the "Search
   Results"screen will appear and the results will be shown as:
     Alien (Wide Screen Edition)
     Alien 3 (Wide Screen Edition)
     Aliens - Die Rückkehr (Director's cut)
     Meine Stiefmutter ist ein Alien
     (as no "case parameter" was defined VA searches  for both, upper  and
     lower case; hence this result)!
   On the top  line of  the "Search Result" screen, the  numbers "001-004"
   are shown to  designate that only four entries from this database  were
   found (that is why the "Next" button is disabled, as there  were only 4
   found).

2) Return to the Search screen and then try the following:
   - tick the "Enable Advanced Search" button.
   - tick the SP/LP cycle button, then select the "SP" as an option.
   Now start the search. The results are as shown below:
     Alien (Wide Screen Edition)
     Alien 3 (Wide Screen Edition)
     Aliens - Die Rückkehr (Director's cut)
   Compare this result with example 1 above? There is  one entry  missing:
   "Meine Stiefmutter ist ein Alien". Why? This  is because this  entry is
   listed as a LP film; but the search parameter was set to display videos
   that were SP.

3) Return to the Search screen:
   - delete the content of the string gadget.
   - untick the SP/LP option.
   - tick the +/- cycle button and select "+" as the option.
   Begin the search. The following film will be shown:-
     Action Jackson
   This is the only video that is shown as "on loan"; ("+" means searching
   for videos that are "on loan!". "-" designates videos not "on loan").


Hopefully  this  will  give the  user a  small  indication  of the  search
potential provided by this programme?

Have fun.


 Back to @{"MainScreen" link "mainscreen_e" 0}

@endnode



@node "Funktion_Print_e" "Print"
@prev "Funktion_Search_e"
@next "Setup_e"

@{b}Print@{ub} (keyboard: "p")
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

The Print option  offers almost unlimited  options to  design your  print-
outs. The main screen "Print" option  can be further enhanced, if combined
with the Search option!

This may sound very  complex, but once understood, the procedure  is quite
simple.

VideoArchiv allows  the  writing  of personal  printer-scripts! These  are
called @{b}"schemes"@{ub} and can be adapted to print any combination of VA data.

Schemes consist of  normal ascii-text. Each  can be  edited using  a text-
editor (ie. ED; CED; GoldED, etc.), and  are  located  in the "VA_Schemes"
directory. Schemes added to  this directory  are  accessible from the main
VideoArchiv programme.

Click the "Print" button  on the  main  screen. The "Print Options" window
will  appear. This  screen  permits  a choice  of a @{b}printer scheme  and an
output path@{ub}. Personal user schemes can  be accessed  by using the "Scheme"
cycle button, but first ensure that  they are located  in the "VA_Schemes"
drawer!
The "Standard scheme" will print the list as shown in either listview, and
is always available.
The "Output" black box is used to enter the path to tell VA where to print
the data. The default option is "PRT:"; this will  print the data via  the
printer. Enter any other  path (ie. "dh1:VA/test.txt"), when  the  wish is
to print to  file for further editing; (ie. this example would "print" the
data to the "VA" directory, located on the "dh1" volume, and the resultant
file will be named "test.txt").

To print the data:
Select the "Print" button from the main screen  to print all of the listed
data.
To print parts  of any  data list, click  the "Search" option; select  the
search  parameters and  click "Search";  from the  "Search Results" window
click  "Print"  and  the "Print Options" screen  will  appear. Follow  the
earlier  explanations  and  configure  the  print  options. Those  entries
matching the search parameters will then be printed.



@{b}How to write a scheme?@{ub}

The procedure is very simple, once understood!

An example of a simple scheme:

@{i};--BEGIN script 1

&VA_Title:0

;--END script 1@{ui}

Explanation: Any  phrase  beginning  with "&VA_" is a command. This  tells
VideoArchiv to replace the  default command  with the new command, and its
relevant data.
The command "&VA_Title" will print the title of each film.

If the print list contains three entries (this example uses part of the VA
default data file; "Filmlist_Demo.vad"), then the printed result would be:

@{i}Alien (Wide Screen Edition)
Alien 3 (Wide Screen Edition)
Action Jackson@{ui}

In the above simple scheme the ":0" tells  VideoArchiv how  to format  the
text to be printed. ":0" means  no formatting, any other number  will tell
VA to insert exactly that amount of chars (ie. if ":10" is  added, and the
title length is 37 chars, only the  first 10 chars will be printed. If the
title  consists  of 7 chars, spaces  will  be  added  until 10  chars  are
printed.


A more complicated example:

@{i};--BEGIN script 2

Film Title: &VA_Title:16  Film length: &VA_Length:0 min

;--END script 2@{ui}

The printed result:

@{i}Film Title: Alien (Wide S...  Film length: 120 min
Film Title: Alien 3 (Dire...  Film length: 115 min
Film Title: Action Jackson    Film length: 95 min@{ui}

This scheme has the following effects:
- any entry that will not fit into the given  space will be cut and "..."
  will be added.
- any text that does not begin with "&VA_" will be printed normally.
- commands with ":0" will not be affected (check the film lengths).

The ":0", or a number, must be added to any created VA scheme.


A final example:

@{i};--BEGIN script 3

&VA_Title:50 &VA_Length:3 min   &VA_Status:0
**************************************************************
Genre   : &VA_Genre:0
Director: &VA_Direc:0
Actor(s): &VA_Actors:0

;--END script 3@{ui}


Using this example the print result would be:

@{ui}@{i}Alien (Wide Screen Edition)                 120  min   OK
**************************************************************
Genre   : Science Fiction / Action
Director: Ridley Scott
Actor(s): Sigourney Weaver, Tom Skerritt

Alien 3 (Wide Screen Edition))                   115  min   OK
**************************************************************
Genre   : Science Fiction / Action
Director: David Fincher
Actor(s): Sigourney Weaver

Action Jackson                                    95  min   XX
**************************************************************
Genre   : 
Director: 
Actor(s): @{ui}


Hopefully the above  examples will give the user the  incentive to experi-
ment and add  their own VA scheme  scripts to enable  a wide set  of print
options.


Listing of all @{b}available commands@{ub} and their meaning:

@{b}&VA_Title      :@{ub} print the title of the film(s).
@{b}&VA_OTitle     :@{ub} print the the original title of the film(s).
@{b}&VA_Year       :@{ub} print the year of the film.
@{b}&VA_Length     :@{ub} print the length of the film entry.
@{b}&VA_SPLP       :@{ub} print the tape speed (ie. SP/LP).
@{b}&VA_Status     :@{ub} print the current availability status:
                 - "OK" if available.
                 - "XX" if "on loan".
@{b}&VA_Genre      :@{ub} print the contents of the Genre box.
@{b}&VA_Direc      :@{ub} print the contents of the Director box.
@{b}&VA_Actors     :@{ub} print the contents of the Actors box.
@{b}&VA_Description:@{ub} print the contents of the description screen.
@{b}&VA_Language   :@{ub} print the language designated (ENG/ITA, etc.).
@{b}&VA_Age        :@{ub} print the age option shown (18/21, etc.).
@{b}&VA_Sound      :@{ub} print the sound option shown (Mono/Stereo, etc.).
@{b}&VA_Format     :@{ub} print the format option shown (PAL/NTSC, etc.).
@{b}&VA_Medium     :@{ub} print the medium option (VHS/CDROM, etc.).
@{b}&VA_Person     :@{ub} print the name, to whom the film is loaned.
@{b}&VA_Date       :@{ub} print the date of issue.

@{b}Further notes:@{ub}
- these commands are case sensitive! Sorry, but we are  not able to change
  this at that moment..
- forget to enter a ":xx" value? A syntax  error will appear, showing  the
  relevant line number containing the mistake.
  ":xx" may be any number, but only  the first 3 digits  will be used (ie.
  10000 - VA will use: 100).
- each script can contain  up to 100 lines, each  line  can contain  up to
  1000 chars. Enough for  anyone? Please  contact the  author if you  dis-
  agree!

It is hoped that any user will agree  that this Print option is a powerful
feature of VideoArchiv...?

Have fun!


 Back to @{"MainScreen" link "mainscreen_e" 0}

@endnode



@node "Setup_e" "Setup"
@prev "Funktion_Print_e"
@next "Funktion_Quit_e"

@{b}Setup@{ub} (keyboard: "u")
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

When the "Setup" button is used, VideoArchiv can be customised to suit any
user's prefered settings.

The Setup screen shows a view screen with the 6 arrow buttons sited to the
right.

The scroll cycle button enables the user to move between each of the three
default view screens. This allows  additions, subtractions, or  sorting of
each list. Each respective list is called to the main Edit or  Add screen,
when each arrow button is used.

Scroll  between the three options, Genre - Director - Actor, and check the
VA default lists, as added by  the authors. Quite a  reasonable selection?
As no two people have the same views, it is inevitable that each user will
wish to alter, add or delete some (or all) of the default entries.

The first two buttons below the cycle button allow  the user  to add (New)
or delete (Del) to each list. The third button allows alphabetical sorting
(Sort). The  two  lower buttons  allow  the user to move up, or down, each
name in whichever list is being viewed.
To  @{b}add  a name@{ub}, click "New" and  the word "<new>" will  appear in the box
below the list.
To @{b}delete a name@{ub}, highlight the name; this will show the name in the lower
box; move the  mouse over the "Del" option, click, and the  entry  will be
deleted.

Each list can  contain 100 names. To add further  names, others need to be
first deleted (sorry but a maximum number had to be arbitrarily set).

Once  satisfied, these listings  can be  saved  by using  the "Save Prefs"
button (sorry registered users only).



@{b}Options@{ub}
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

The Options screen allows  the user  to further  customise the VideoArchiv
default settings:

@{b}Fade Rate:@{ub}  (default: 10).
By using the up or down  arrow  button, this number can be altered between
1 and 99. This alters the time between each  VideoArchiv screen's  appear-
ance. Lower numbers = faster, higher numbers = slower.

@{b}Create Backup:@{ub} (default: ticked).
This tells the programme to  create a backup file, whenever  the main file
is saved. Leave blank if this option is not required.
The name of the backup file will be: <name of videoarchiv file>.BAK

@{b}Edit Film by double click:@{ub} (default: blank).
If left blank, this option  requires the "Edit" button to  be  used on the
main screen. If ticked, the user can edit  entries by double clicking  any
video entry.

@{b}Use Standards if data not set:@{ub} (default: ticked).
This tells VideoArchiv to  use the default standard settings  whenever you
add a new film. This option  is also useful  when old files (from previous
versions) are loaded and require gaps to be filled.

@{b}Standard Settings:@{ub}
These are the multiple options that can be set by the user.
The 6 cycle buttons can easily be altered to be used as the "user default"
settings.

Cycle button:         Available options                         Default
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Video speed (Type)  : SP, LP                                    (SP)
Viewing Age (Age)   : 8, 10, 12, 14, 16, 18, 20, 21, 25, ---    (16)
Screen Mode (Format): PAL, NTSC, 16:9, PAL+, HDTV, ---          (PAL)
Language            : ENG, GER, ITA, FRE, SPA, SWE, ---         (ENG)
Sound               : Mono, Stereo, DSP, THX, AC-3, ---         (Stereo)
Tape Type (Medium)  : VHS, S-VHS, Hi8, LD, CDI, CDROM, DVD, --- (VHS)

Use "---" if you do not like these default settings.

@{b}Load/Save Path - Load File at Startup@{ub}
These two path options allow the user to direct VideoArchiv to load which-
ever file is to be loaded by default, whenever the programme is started.
If the user  creates a  directory (say ABC) within  the  main  VideoArchiv
directory the settings could be as shown:
  Load/Save Path:        dh1:VideoArchiv_v3.0/
If the user names the first created database File1 the setting would be:
  Load File at Startup:  ABC/File1



@{b}Palette@{ub} (keyboard: "p")
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

The "Palette" button allows  the user to  edit all colours  used by Video-
Archiv. By moving the  mouse over  the  various colour  squares, and  then
clicking, the  palette  used by the  programme can  be altered. The  three
slide bars also allow more fine tuning, if required.

The palette buttons allow the user to:
 @{b}Copy to@{ub}
 @{b}Exchange@{ub}
 @{b}Spread to@{ub}
 @{b}Use Standard settings@{ub}
Rather than write pages of  suggestions it is easier for  the user to play
around  with the  three sliders, and the buttons, and  watch  the  colours
change. If the user requires to return to the VideoArchiv default colours,
click the "Standard" button.


Back in the main setup screen, you are able  to use  one of the  following
options:

@{b}Save Prefs@{ub}
The settings are saved by  using the "Save Prefs" button (registered users
only). These settings are saved in the file called VA.config.

@{b}Load Prefs@{ub}
Use the "Load" button to reload any saved preferences.

@{b}Standard@{ub}
If the user requires to return to the VideoArchiv  default settings, click
the "Standard" button.

@{b}Use@{ub}
Click the "Use" button to return to the main screen.


Once the users VideoArchiv database has been created, it is suggested that
these various options be tested to enhance further useage.

Enjoy.


 Back to @{"MainScreen" link "mainscreen_e" 0}

@endnode



@node "Funktion_Quit_e" "Quit"
@prev "Setup_e"
@next ""

@{b}Quit@{ub} (keyboard: "q")
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

This will quit the programme.

There is an error message added that  will show  if the user tries to exit
with unsaved alterations:
  "Request Are you sure that you want to quit?
   (current changes will be lost!)."
Use "OK" to quit, or "Exit" to return to the programme.


 Back to @{"MainScreen" link "mainscreen_e" 0}

@endnode



@node "Future_e" "Future"
@prev "main"
@next ""

@{b}Known Problems@{ub}
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

@{b}Screen Mode:@{ub}
To date it is not possible to alter the screen mode for VideoArchiv (it is
hoped to add this option to later versions). VideoArchiv requires  a high-
res screen (PAL 640x256). This is  the Standard  Workbench  resolution. If
you are unable to open such a  screen on your system, you may  not be able
to run VideoArchiv correctly.

@{b}Font Type:@{ub}
Sorry but VideoArchiv  is not yet written  in a font  sensitive  way. This
means that VA uses the workbench standard, topaz font 8.
Problems may be experienced if patches are installed to replace  the topaz
font with a user defined font.

@{b}Black Screen:@{ub}
If a black screen is  displayed when VA is started, delete the "VA.config"
file and restart the programme.


Please contact the authors if any other difficulties are detected.

Please register and keep Amiga programmers alive, and well.
Thank you for using VideoArchiv.



@{b}To Do@{ub}
--------------------------------------------------------------------------

 - develop faster load and save routines.

 - Movie Database import option.

 - more amiga style guide compatibility ;-).

 - user defined font option.

 - different screen modes.

...

 - Any suggestions...?
   Please send us any suggestions that you feel might enhance VideoArchiv.

@endnode

